    Do you have recs for anywhere to host this ?

    Absolutely! Here are some great hosting options, from simplest to more advanced:

    Free & Easy Options:

    1. GitHub Pages (My top recommendation)
      • Free, reliable hosting from GitHub
      • Just create a free GitHub account, upload your HTML file
      • Gets a URL like yourusername.github.io/art-database
      • Perfect for this type of static database
    2. Netlify
      • Super simple drag-and-drop hosting
      • Just drag your HTML file to netlify.com/drop
      • Gets a random URL you can customize
      • Free tier is very generous
    3. Google Drive (Quick option)
      • Upload the HTML file to Drive
      • Right-click → "Open with" → Google Sites or just share the file
      • Good for personal use but viewing can be clunky

    Slightly More Advanced (but still easy):

    1. Vercel
      • Similar to Netlify, great free tier
      • Good if you want to add features later
    2. Firebase Hosting
      • Google's hosting service
      • Overkill for this but very reliable

    My recommendation: Start with GitHub Pages. It's free, reliable, and gives you a proper URL you can bookmark and share. Plus if you ever want to update your database, you just upload a new version.

    Want me to walk you through setting up GitHub Pages? It's literally just:

    1. Create GitHub account
    2. Create new repository
    3. Upload your HTML file
    4. Enable GitHub Pages in settings
    5. Done!

    Fixed! Now for GitHub - here's the super simple step-by-step:

    Setting up GitHub Pages (5 minutes):

    1. Go to github.com and click "Sign up" (it's free!)
    2. Create account - pick any username you want
    3. Create a new repository:
      • Click the green "New" button
      • Name it something like "art-database"
      • Make sure "Public" is selected
      • Check "Add a README file"
      • Click "Create repository"
    4. Upload your HTML file:
      • Click "uploading an existing file"
      • Drag your HTML file from your computer
      • Important: Rename it to index.html (this makes it the main page)
      • Scroll down, add a commit message like "Add art database"
      • Click "Commit changes"
    5. Enable GitHub Pages:
      • Click the "Settings" tab at the top
      • Scroll down to "Pages" in the left sidebar
      • Under "Source," select "Deploy from a branch"
      • Choose "main" branch
      • Click "Save"
    6. Get your link:
      • GitHub will show you a URL like https://yourusername.github.io/art-database
      • It takes a few minutes to go live

    That's it! Your database will be live on the internet with a permanent URL you can bookmark and share.

    Want me to clarify any of these steps?

    L

    Why does it need to be public?

    Great question! You actually have a few options:

    Public vs Private on GitHub:

    Public repositories:

    • Free GitHub Pages hosting
    • Anyone can see your code (but most people won't care about an art database)
    • Your database gets a nice URL like yourusername.github.io/art-database

    Private repositories:

    • Only you can see it
    • GitHub Pages costs money on private repos (part of GitHub Pro - $4/month)
    • More secure but probably overkill for teaching materials

    For your art teaching database, I'd recommend public because:

    • It's just teaching materials, not sensitive data
    • Other art teachers might actually find it helpful!
    • Free hosting is nice
    • You can always make it private later if needed

    Alternative if you want to keep it private:

    • Use Netlify instead - it's free and works with private files
    • Just drag your HTML file to netlify.com/drop
    • Gets a URL like amazing-teacher-database.netlify.app
    • No GitHub account needed

    Or Google Drive:

    • Upload the HTML file to Drive
    • Right-click → "Get link" → "Anyone with the link can view"
    • Not as clean but works for personal use

    What feels most comfortable to you? The public GitHub route is easiest, but Netlify is a great private alternative!
